                                <condition key="deficient">
                                  The sewing thread is broken in many points and the quires shift one onto the others. The long stripe of cloth that serves to protect the edges of the codex is almost detatched from the cover.
                                  The leaves are in good conditions. The manufacture of the parchment is very accurated, the surface is smooth and without traces of hairs.
                                  The leaves are stained with dirt along the lower margin showing the signs of intense use.
                                </condition>

                            </supportDesc>

                            <layoutDesc>
                              <layout columns="2" writtenLines="20">
                                <note>Data on dimension are taken from <locus target="#91r">fol. 91r</locus>.</note>
                                <locus from="5r" to="187r">Fols 5r–187r</locus>
                                <dimensions unit="mm">
                                  <height>142</height>
                                  <width>120</width>
                                </dimensions>
                                <dimensions type="margin">
                                  <dim type="top">33</dim>
                                  <dim type="bottom">49</dim>
                                  <dim type="right">26</dim>
                                  <dim type="left">13</dim>
                                </dimensions>
                                <ab type="ruling" subtype="pattern">1-1-11/0/0/C</ab>
                                <ab type="pricking" subtype="pattern">
                                  The layout corresponds to the pattern I defined by D. Nosnitsin: the text is written above the first ruled line, the vertical and horizontal pricks are visible
                                  and they are located in the margins.
                                  The pricks are small, round and precise. Probably, the pricking was made opening the quires in the middle and piercing the folios together.
                                  </ab>
                              </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
